{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563638"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16842"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16842"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.44,0.06,0.03,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110541"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9532"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92797"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"593"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1507"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43663"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110541"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with heavy vaginal bleeding and lower abdominal cramping for the past three hours. She is eight weeks pregnant by her last menstrual period. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. She has had one previous uncomplicated pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale and diaphoretic. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with mild suprapubic tenderness. Speculum examination reveals an open cervix with heavy ongoing bright red vaginal bleeding with clots. There are no products visible in the cervix. Ultrasound shows an intrauterine pregnancy with FHR 80bpm at eight weeks gestation. Her haemoglobin is 87 g/L (115-160). Estimated blood loss is greater than 1.5 L with ongoing heavy fresh PV loss.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intramuscular anti-D immunoglobulin","Urgent suction curettage","Expectant management with close observation","Medical management with misoprostol","Blood transfusion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a life-threatening haemorrhage in early pregnancy, evidenced by significant blood loss (\u0026gt;1.5 L), tachycardia (120/min), hypotension (90/60 mmHg), and a low haemoglobin (87 g/L). Despite the presence of fetal cardiac activity, the immediate priority is maternal stabilisation. This is a case of inevitable miscarriage, characterized by heavy vaginal bleeding, open cervical os, and a very low fetal heart rate of 80bpm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent suction curettage\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management as it provides definitive control of bleeding. The procedure should be performed in theatre with appropriate anaesthetic support and after blood products have been cross-matched. While fetal cardiac activity is present, the severity of maternal compromise necessitates immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous in this scenario given the haemodynamic instability and ongoing heavy blood loss. This approach carries a significant risk of further deterioration and potentially catastrophic outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical management with misoprostol\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it takes several hours to be effective and would not provide the rapid haemostasis required in this emergency situation. It is more suitable for stable patients with incomplete miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not address the underlying cause of bleeding. While this patient has a low haemoglobin (85 g/L), blood transfusion is typically reserved for haemoglobin levels below 70 g/L in otherwise healthy patients. The priority is to stop the bleeding through surgical intervention. Once bleeding is controlled, the patient may require iron replacement therapy rather than blood transfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular anti-D immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the patient is Rhesus negative, but this is not the immediate priority. It can be administered once haemodynamic stability has been achieved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConcurrent resuscitation with intravenous fluids should be initiated while preparing for theatre. The key principle is that maternal wellbeing takes precedence over fetal viability when there is significant haemodynamic compromise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Heavy vaginal bleeding in early pregnancy with haemodynamic compromise requires urgent surgical management regardless of fetal viability.","Transvaginal ultrasound is essential to confirm intrauterine pregnancy and exclude ectopic pregnancy before surgical management.","Blood products should be cross-matched before surgical evacuation in cases of significant blood loss."],"references":["Hezelgrave NL, Shand AW. Massive haemorrhage in early pregnancy [Internet]. O\u0026G Magazine. 2013 [cited 2024 Dec 4];15(1). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/15/1-15/massive-haemorrhage-early-pregnancy/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92797"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92797"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-01T08:15:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T10:21:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9532"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110541"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships